    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>SIN&#xAD;GA&#xAD;PORE FILMS SLATED FOR RE&#xAD;LEASE THIS YEAR</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-14"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210114/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-14">2021-01-14</a></time> -
        

            <a href="/category/tag-268435461/en/sg">Entertainment</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268486116/en/sg">Filmmaking</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268449474/en/sg">Movies</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-536891206/en/sg">Singapore</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068136/en/sg">Germany</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068547/en/sg">Calcutta</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068969/en/sg">Montevideo</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540449450/en/sg">William Shakespeare</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068074/en/sg">Asia</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537084737/en/sg">Youtube</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068227/en/sg">Taiwan</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-539155588/en/sg">Alien Huang</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537693097/en/sg">Alien</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-541116034/en/sg">Singapore University of Social Sciences</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538059755/en/sg">Locarno</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540442000/en/sg">Jack Neo</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540830750/en/sg">Mark Lee</a>     </section>

        <p>FAT HOPE</p>
        <p>Re­lease: First quar­ter Di­rec­tor: Joyce Lee</p>
        <p>Af­ter co-di­rect­ing the cos­play story Young And Fab­u­lous (2016), di­rec­tor Joyce Lee makes her solo fea­ture de­but with this body-swop com­edy.</p>
        <p>Tai­wanese ac­tress Lin Yu-pin (above, right) plays a model zapped with a curse that ren­ders her sev­eral sizes larger. The film ex­plores ide­alised images of body size in the me­dia and stars Tai­wanese ac­tor-host-singer Alien Huang (above, left) in one of his fi­nal roles be­fore his sud­den death by aor­tic dis­sec­tion last Septem­ber.</p>
        <p>THE MAN ON THE OTHER SIDE</p>
        <p>Re­lease: Se­lected dates this and next month at mil­i­tancy.eventbrite.sg, at Ea­glew­ings Cine­mat­ics, with screen­ing up­dates on in­sta­gram.com/Manon­theother­side</p>
        <p>Sin­ga­porean writer-di­rec­tor Mar­cus Lim says he does not speak a word of Ger­man but he made this mostly Ger­man-lan­guage film, shot in Germany with a cast of mostly Ger­man ac­tors.</p>
        <p>He calls his fea­ture de­but a “retro spy film”. Set dur­ing the height of the 1970s Cold War ten­sion, the thriller stars Mari Bensel as So­phie Zim­mer­man, a thief hunted by forces on both sides of the Iron Cur­tain.</p>
        <p>The film has picked up awards at the Cal­cutta In­ter­na­tional Cult Film Fes­ti­val and the Mon­te­v­ideo World Film Fes­ti­val, among oth­ers.</p>
        <p>Lim is an as­so­ciate lec­turer in the Film Stud­ies Department at the Sin­ga­pore Univer­sity of So­cial Sci­ences. He spe­cialises in screen­writ­ing and Shake­speare on film and has writ­ten for Chan­nel 5’s crime drama se­ries Code Of Law (2012 to present).</p>
        <p>YUNI Re­lease: Di­rec­tor:</p>
        <p>First or sec­ond quar­ter Kamila An­dini</p>
        <p>Akanga Film Asia, the Sin­ga­pore-based la­bel be­hind the drama A Land Imag­ined (2018), win­ner of the Golden Leop­ard at the Lo­carno Film Fes­ti­val, will show­case this Sin­ga­pore-French-In­done­sian pro­duc­tion. Writ­ten and di­rected by In­done­sian film-maker Kamila An­dini, 34, this com­ing-of-age drama stars YouTu­ber Arawinda Ki­rana (above, in pur­ple) as the ti­tle char­ac­ter, a teenager who has to choose be­tween fig­ur­ing out what she wants from life and tak­ing up one of the of­fers of mar­riage she has at­tracted.</p>
        <p>AN­DRE AND HIS OLIVE TREE Re­lease: Today</p>
        <p>Di­rec­tor: Josiah Ng</p>
        <p>Sin­ga­porean di­rec­tor Josiah Ng wanted to premiere this bi­og­ra­phy of chef An­dre Chi­ang here. Then “the pan­demic hit and dis­tri­bu­tion in Sin­ga­pore be­came un­cer­tain”, he tells The Straits Times.</p>
        <p>So last year, the doc­u­men­tary opened in Chi­ang’s home coun­try, Tai­wan, be­cause cin­e­mas were op­er­at­ing more or less nor­mally. The team con­sid­ered send­ing the film to an online plat­form but de­cided against it be­cause Ng says the film was made with the­atres in mind.</p>
        <p>“It was a bless­ing in dis­guise,” he says, be­cause the film, cap­tur­ing Chi­ang’s shock clo­sure of his Restau­rant An­dre in Bukit Pa­soh Road and the re­turn­ing of his two Miche­lin stars, went on to be­come last year’s high­est-gross­ing doc­u­men­tary in Tai­wan. See re­view on C3.</p>
        <p>OTH­ERS</p>
        <p>Jack Neo’s drama-com­edy The Diam Diam Era Two, the fol­low-up to last Novem­ber’s The Diam Diam Era, will be re­leased on Feb 11.</p>
        <p>Diam Diam ac­tor Mark Lee is the di­rec­tor of the creepy Hell Bank Presents: Run­ning Ghost, about a man who, af­ter dy­ing, finds that he can get a sec­ond chance at life if he wins the af­ter­life re­al­ity show Run­ning Ghost. It also opens in the first quar­ter.</p>
        <p>Pre­cious Is The Night, a drama di­rected by Tai­wan’s Wayne Peng and star­ring Sin­ga­porean pho­tog­ra­pher, model and so­cial me­dia star Chuando Tan (be­low), will be re­leased in March.</p>
        <p>The mon­ster movie set in un­der­ground tun­nels Cir­cle Line, di­rected by Chua Jing Du, should open in the sec­ond quar­ter.</p>
        <p>The thriller Shad­ows, di­rected by Glenn Chan, about a psy­chi­a­trist who can en­ter the sub­con­scious mind of oth­ers, also opens in the sec­ond quar­ter.</p>
        <p>Be­ing re­leased in the third quar­ter is The Fate­keep­ers, di­rected by Daniel Yam, a thriller about five peo­ple who find them­selves the hold­ers of a se­cret, pow­er­ful force.</p>
        <p>The hor­ror an­thol­ogy Late Night Ride opens in the fourth quar­ter and re­lates three sto­ries, each set in a car, a bus and on a bi­cy­cle, about the scary things that can hap­pen when trav­el­ling af­ter sun­down.</p>

